			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Bards new Epic look.<a name="62075"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 15 04 10:48 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>It's a saber. As in the Marine NCO &quot;sword&quot; (which was originally the Army cavalry saber). You can tell by the curve in the blade. Originally, the sabers were basic straight swords, but they soon realized that galloping full stride at a target, sliding it through their chest, spinning him around as you passed and pulling it out as you leave (with your arm behind you, looks really strange) lead to the blade breaking off inside the target more often then not. They had to be thick enough to withstand the shock of puncturing the ribcage with such force, but flexible enough to survive the &quot;whip&quot; effect of slashing and sudden direction changes used in cavalry fighting techniques. It also needed an edge on it in order to perform the different slashing techniques. I only know all this because I visited the Leeds Armory in Leeds, UK last year and spent about 6 hours in that museum. That place is absolutely awesome. They even let us try on some original (as in hundreds of years old) chainmail and full suits of original conquistador armor. We were a military tour group though, so that may have been a special deal.
<br />

<br />
And I think what you're seeing as part of a whip in the picture is actually supposed to be either to make it look like it's moving (drawing techniques, you know?) or possible a partical effect. It doesn't look like a part of the weapon itself.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
